---
// Colophon — how the site is built (stack, design, principles, build note).
// Static page — prerender to HTML served from the CDN (output: 'server' is on-demand by default).
export const prerender = true;
import { css } from 'styled-system/css';
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '../components/PageHeader.astro';

const para = css({ color: 'textMuted', lineHeight: 1.8, mb: '1rem' });
const h2 = css({ fontSize: '1.3rem', fontWeight: 700, mt: '2.25rem', mb: '0.75rem' });
const list = css({ color: 'textMuted', lineHeight: 1.9, pl: '1.25rem', mb: '1rem' });
const link = css({ color: 'primary', textDecoration: 'underline', _hover: { color: 'primaryHover' } });
const term = css({ color: 'text', fontWeight: 600 });
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Colophon"
  description="How patricksaade.com is built — the stack, design choices, and principles behind the site."
>
  <PageHeader breadcrumbs={[{ label: 'Home', href: '/' }, { label: 'Colophon' }]} eyebrow="Colophon" title="How this site is built" description="What it's built with, and why it works the way it does." />

  <p class={para}>
    I designed this to be fast, readable, and private — static HTML with a little inline
    JavaScript, and nothing following you around. No cookies, no marketing trackers, and the
    analytics are cookieless (the full story is in the <a class={link} href="/privacy/">privacy
    policy</a>). It's semantic, keyboard-friendly, and it respects reduced motion.
  </p>

  <h2 class={h2}>Built with</h2>
  <ul class={list}>
    <li><a class={link} href="https://astro.build" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Astro</a> — the framework; every page is prerendered to static HTML.</li>
    <li><a class={link} href="https://panda-css.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Panda CSS</a> — zero-runtime styling, generated at build time.</li>
    <li><a class={link} href="https://mdxjs.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">MDX</a> — how I write the posts.</li>
    <li><a class={link} href="https://shiki.style" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Shiki</a> — syntax highlighting, themed light and dark.</li>
    <li><a class={link} href="https://floating-ui.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Floating UI</a> — the hover cards on terms, tools, and companies.</li>
    <li><a class={link} href="https://github.com/vercel/satori" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Satori</a> — the social / Open Graph card images, rendered at build time.</li>
    <li><a class={link} href="https://vercel.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Vercel</a> — hosting, the global CDN, and cookieless Web Analytics &amp; Speed Insights.</li>
    <li>Type — <a class={link} href="https://www.redaction.us" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Redaction</a>, by Jeremy Mickel (<a class={link} href="https://www.mckltype.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">MCKL</a>), drawn for Titus Kaphar &amp; Reginald Dwayne Betts' <em>The Redaction</em>. It comes in graded levels of degradation — I run the eroded grades on the wordmark, hero, and ticker. Used under the <a class={link} href="/fonts/redaction/OFL.txt">SIL Open Font License</a>.</li>
    <li>Code is set in <a class={link} href="https://github.com/mozilla/Fira" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Fira Mono</a> (Mozilla), under the <a class={link} href="/fonts/fira-mono/OFL.txt">SIL Open Font License</a>. The icons are <a class={link} href="https://lucide.dev" target="_blank" rel="noopener">lucide</a>-style SVGs I draw inline so they follow the theme.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class={h2}>A few details</h2>
  <p class={para}>
    Ten color themes — five dark, five light — that you pick independently per mode, with a circular
    wipe when you switch. An ambient node-field background tuned to the active palette, and a retro
    custom cursor on the desktop. Press <span class={term}>⌘K</span> to search the whole site, and
    turn on optional <span class={term}>interface sounds</span> from the nav. It's an installable PWA,
    so pages stay readable offline — with a small indicator when you drop your connection.
  </p>
  <p class={para}>
    The reference side runs deep and cross-linked: a searchable <span class={term}>Glossary</span> of
    500+ security concepts (with a fresh <span class={term}>Term of the Day</span> each morning), a
    free &amp; open-source <span class={term}>tools</span> directory, and a full
    <a class={link} href="https://attack.mitre.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">MITRE ATT&amp;CK</a>
    Coverage Map — the entire Enterprise matrix, generated from MITRE's official ATT&amp;CK data, with a
    detail page for every technique — paired with its defensive counterpart, a
    <a class={link} href="https://d3fend.mitre.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">MITRE D3FEND</a>
    map of countermeasures, two-way linked so each technique shows what defends against it.
    ATT&amp;CK® and D3FEND™ are trademarks of The MITRE Corporation.
  </p>

  <h2 class={h2}>The build</h2>
  <p class={para}>
    Straight up: I built the design and front-end with AI assistance
    (<a class={link} href="https://claude.com/claude-code" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Claude Code</a>),
    then reviewed and refined every piece myself. The source is on
    <a class={link} href="https://github.com/patsaade/personal-portfolio" target="_blank" rel="noopener">GitHub</a>,
    and the footer links the exact build version and commit.
  </p>
</BaseLayout>
